{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01BS6yBfrTWu8ZEaNgMDU9CX","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge\n2\t\n3\tFirst hands-on internship assignment: apply Nielsen Norman's 10 Usability Heuristics to Kubernetes-style interfaces across multiple AI tools and compare their analysis quality.\n4\t\n5\t## The Jagged Edge\n6\t\n7\tResearch from Harvard Business School shows AI capabilities aren't uniform — models are very good at some tasks and surprisingly bad at others. The boundary between \"good\" and \"bad\" isn't obvious. This is the \"jagged technological frontier.\"\n8\t\n9\t## What Was Tested\n10\t\n11\t- Selected Kubernetes/OpenShift UI screens at different complexity levels\n12\t- Crafted evaluation prompts asking each tool to assess against all 10 heuristics with severity ratings (1–4)\n13\t- Ran the same prompt through Cursor, Claude Code, Gemini (Flash + Pro), and ChatGPT\n14\t\n15\t## Comparison Dimensions\n16\t\n17\t- Quality of analysis — did it correctly identify real usability issues?\n18\t- Depth — surface-level observations vs. genuine insight?\n19\t- Specificity — generic advice vs. grounded in the actual interface?\n20\t- Structure — how well-organized and actionable?\n21\t- Hallucinations — did it make things up?\n22\t- Unique insights — did any tool catch something others missed?\n23\t\n24\t## Deliverables\n25\t\n26\t- [Jaquez - Task 1 - Nielsen & Agents](https://docs.google.com/document/d/11o9Px8wddeal3Ap7vBVtyDSw8FWaMGsuTYQwyc0hSAQ) (Google Doc)\n27\t- [Update — Evan Jaquez](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1AoUZtCCJf4btr68jOY3_xKbJU2wyx6XTqjGn6IIRd3w) (Google Slides)\n28\t\n29\t## Relevance to Current Work\n30\t\n31\tThe comparison methodology directly informs the [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — understanding which AI tools produce research-quality heuristic evaluations vs. shallow summaries is critical for choosing the right approach to automated prototype evaluation.\n32\t\n33\t## Related\n34\t\n35\t- [UX Quality Rubric](ux-quality-rubric.md) — rubric-based scoring approach\n36\t- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — applies these learnings\n37\t- [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) — where evaluations will be used\n38\t- [Ansible AI Helpers Strategy — 2026-06-17](ansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md) — heuristic eval skill selected as Ansible pilot\n39\t- [Standup — June 29](standup-2026-06-29.md) — usability comparison approach being iterated on\n40\t- [RH AI-First UX — June 25](rh-ai-first-ux-2026-06-25.md) — unified testing strategy connects to heuristic methodology\n41\t- [Weekly Design Sync — July 1](weekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md) — team agreed to adopt Nielsen's heuristics as base rubric for evaluations\n42\t\n43\t## Sources\n44\t\n45\t- sources/2026-06-03-nielsen-agents-task1.html\n46\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"68e7c754-26f5-4a6d-aea1-fe4bb4ab9f58","uuid":"588916ad-c326-47b1-997b-afbe651595c2","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:55:53.362Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md","content":"# Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge\n\nFirst hands-on internship assignment: apply Nielsen Norman's 10 Usability Heuristics to Kubernetes-style interfaces across multiple AI tools and compare their analysis quality.\n\n## The Jagged Edge\n\nResearch from Harvard Business School shows AI capabilities aren't uniform — models are very good at some tasks and surprisingly bad at others. The boundary between \"good\" and \"bad\" isn't obvious. This is the \"jagged technological frontier.\"\n\n## What Was Tested\n\n- Selected Kubernetes/OpenShift UI screens at different complexity levels\n- Crafted evaluation prompts asking each tool to assess against all 10 heuristics with severity ratings (1–4)\n- Ran the same prompt through Cursor, Claude Code, Gemini (Flash + Pro), and ChatGPT\n\n## Comparison Dimensions\n\n- Quality of analysis — did it correctly identify real usability issues?\n- Depth — surface-level observations vs. genuine insight?\n- Specificity — generic advice vs. grounded in the actual interface?\n- Structure — how well-organized and actionable?\n- Hallucinations — did it make things up?\n- Unique insights — did any tool catch something others missed?\n\n## Deliverables\n\n- [Jaquez - Task 1 - Nielsen & Agents](https://docs.google.com/document/d/11o9Px8wddeal3Ap7vBVtyDSw8FWaMGsuTYQwyc0hSAQ) (Google Doc)\n- [Update — Evan Jaquez](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1AoUZtCCJf4btr68jOY3_xKbJU2wyx6XTqjGn6IIRd3w) (Google Slides)\n\n## Relevance to Current Work\n\nThe comparison methodology directly informs the [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — understanding which AI tools produce research-quality heuristic evaluations vs. shallow summaries is critical for choosing the right approach to automated prototype evaluation.\n\n## Related\n\n- [UX Quality Rubric](ux-quality-rubric.md) — rubric-based scoring approach\n- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — applies these learnings\n- [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) — where evaluations will be used\n- [Ansible AI Helpers Strategy — 2026-06-17](ansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md) — heuristic eval skill selected as Ansible pilot\n- [Standup — June 29](standup-2026-06-29.md) — usability comparison approach being iterated on\n- [RH AI-First UX — June 25](rh-ai-first-ux-2026-06-25.md) — unified testing strategy connects to heuristic methodology\n- [Weekly Design Sync — July 1](weekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md) — team agreed to adopt Nielsen's heuristics as base rubric for evaluations\n\n## Sources\n\n- sources/2026-06-03-nielsen-agents-task1.html\n","numLines":46,"startLine":1,"totalLines":46}}}
